  "prompt": "What are the main reasons why students from Boston University don't graduate on time?",
  "response": "While Boston University has a pretty good graduation rate, some students do take longer than four years to graduate. Here are some of the main reasons why:\n\n**Academic Challenges & Choices:**\n\n*   **Changing Majors/Programs:** This is a common reason. Switching majors, especially multiple times, can lead to missed prerequisites, require extra courses, and push back graduation timelines.\n*   **Difficult Course Load/Academic Performance:** Struggling in challenging courses, failing courses, or having a lower GPA than required can force students to retake classes or take a lighter course load to catch up. Some students may require academic probation or be required to take time off to improve their academic standing.\n*   **Intensive Programs:** Some programs, like those involving significant lab work, research, or clinical requirements, may inherently require more time than four years to complete.\n*   **Adding a Minor or Double Major:** While enriching, adding a minor or double major significantly increases the course load and can easily extend the graduation timeline.\n*   **Study Abroad:** Depending on the program and how credits transfer, studying abroad can sometimes add time to graduation if required courses aren't available or if credit transfer is complicated.\n\n**Financial Reasons:**\n\n*   **Cost of Attendance:** The high cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses can force students to work part-time or even full-time jobs while attending school. This can limit the number of courses they can take each semester.\n*   **Unexpected Financial Emergencies:** Unexpected medical bills, family emergencies, or job loss can force students to take time off to earn money or manage their finances.\n\n**Personal & Health Reasons:**\n\n*   **Physical or Mental Health Issues:** Dealing with physical illness, mental health challenges (like anxiety or depression), or learning disabilities can significantly impact academic performance and require students to take time off or reduce their course load.\n*   **Family Responsibilities:** Students may have family obligations, such as caring for a sick family member or raising children, which can make it difficult to balance school and personal life.\n*   **Burnout:** The pressure to succeed and maintain a high GPA can lead to burnout, which can make it difficult to stay motivated and focused on academics.\n\n**Other Factors:**\n\n*   **Internships and Co-ops:** While valuable for career development, extended internships or co-op programs can delay graduation if they require taking a semester or year off from traditional coursework.\n*   **Limited Course Availability:** Sometimes, required courses may not be offered frequently enough, making it difficult to complete them within a four-year timeframe.\n*   **Lack of Advising or Support:** While BU has advising resources, some students may not effectively utilize them or may not receive adequate guidance in navigating their academic path. This can lead to poor course selection or a lack of awareness about available resources.\n\n**In summary, a combination of academic, financial, personal, and logistical factors can contribute to students at Boston University taking longer than four years to graduate. It's important to remember that everyone's situation is unique, and there's no shame in taking the time needed to complete a degree successfully.**\n",
